# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: bypass-ratio
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:bypass-ratio/a330neo] The **Airbus A330neo** ("neo" for "New Engine Option") is a wide-body airliner developed by Airbus from the original Airbus A330 (now A330*ceo* – "Current Engine Option").
[src:bypass-ratio/a330neo] A new version with modern engines comparable with those developed for the Boeing 787 was called for by operators of the A330ceo.
[src:bypass-ratio/a330neo] It was launched on 14 July 2014 at the Farnborough Airshow, promising 14% better fuel economy per seat.
[src:bypass-ratio/a330neo] It is exclusively powered by the Rolls-Royce Trent 7000 which has double the bypass ratio of its predecessor.
[src:bypass-ratio/a330neo] The -900 made its maiden flight on 19 October 2017 and received its EASA type certificate on 26 September 2018; it was first delivered to TAP Air Portugal on 26 November 2018 and entered service on 15 December.
[src:bypass-ratio/a330neo] The -800 made its first flight on 6 November 2018 and received EASA type certification on 13 February 2020; the first two -800s were delivered to Kuwait Airways on 29 October 2020 and entered service on 20 November.
[src:bypass-ratio/a330neo] As of May 2026, a total of 474 A330neo family aircraft had been ordered by more than 30 customers, of which 195 aircraft had been delivered.
[src:bypass-ratio/a330neo] At the Boeing 787 launch in 2004, Airbus' initial response was an improved A330.
[src:bypass-ratio/a330neo] After negative feedback from airlines and lessors, the A350 XWB became a new design in 2006.
[src:bypass-ratio/a330neo] After the A320neo launch in December 2010 and its commercial success, the largest airline of Malaysia, AirAsia – an all-Airbus operator – asked Airbus to re-engine the A330.
[src:bypass-ratio/a330neo] New engines like the GEnx or Rolls-Royce Trent 1000 developed for the 787 could offer a 12%–15% fuel burn improvement, and sharklets at least 2%.
[src:bypass-ratio/a330neo] Airbus sales chief John Leahy's argument was that the lower purchase price of an A330 even without new engines make the economics of buying an A330 competitive at midrange routes with that of the Boeing 787.
[src:bypass-ratio/a330neo] An A330neo would accelerate the demise of the similarly sized A350-800.
[src:bypass-ratio/a330neo] Airbus also considered re-engining the A380 but was wary of having two major modification programs simultaneously.
[src:bypass-ratio/a330neo] In March 2014, Delta Air Lines expressed an interest in the A330neo to replace its ageing, 20+-year-old Boeing 767-300ER jets.
[src:bypass-ratio/a330neo] In the 250-300-seat market, CIT Group believed an A330neo enables profitability on shorter ranges where the longer-range A350 and Boeing 787 are not optimised.
[src:bypass-ratio/a330neo] CIT said that the A350-800 was not as efficient as it would like, and Air Lease Corp. added that the company did not consider it reasonable to take the A350-800 and A330neo as they saw no sustainable coexistence of the two aircraft.
[src:bypass-ratio/a330neo] AirAsia X ended flights to London and Paris from Kuala Lumpur in 2012 because their Airbus A340s were not fuel-efficient enough and would try again with A330s.
[src:bypass-ratio/a330neo] As Airbus gradually increased the output of the new A350, prolonging the production run of the A330 could help to maintain profitability.
[src:bypass-ratio/a330neo] After Emirates cancelled 70 orders for the A350, Airbus said it continued to work on re-engining the smaller A330.
[src:bypass-ratio/a330neo] On 14 July 2014 at the Farnborough Airshow, Airbus launched the A330neo programme, to be powered by the new Rolls-Royce Trent 7000.
[src:bypass-ratio/a330neo] It would improve the fuel burn per seat by 14%.
[src:bypass-ratio/a330neo] Airbus hoped to sell 1,000 A330neo aircraft.
[src:bypass-ratio/a330neo] Its range would increase by 400 nautical miles (740 km; 460 mi) and although 95% of the parts would be common with the A330ceo, maintenance costs would be lower.
[src:bypass-ratio/a330neo] New winglets, 3.7 metres wider and similar to those of the A350 XWB, still within ICAO category E airport requirements, along with new engine pylons, would improve aerodynamics by 4%.
[src:bypass-ratio/a330neo] The A330neo's development costs, an estimated $2 billion (£1.18 billion) , were expected to have an impact of around −0.7% on Airbus's return on sales target from 2015 to 2017.
[src:bypass-ratio/a330neo] Airbus stated that lower capital cost would make the A330neo the most cost-efficient medium-range wide-body airliner.
[src:bypass-ratio/a330neo] Airbus said that it could pursue demand for 4,000 aircraft and that there was an open market for 2,600 jets not already addressed by backlogs with operators already using A330s.
[src:bypass-ratio/a330neo] Aerodynamic modifications would include a re-twisted wing and optimised slats.
[src:bypass-ratio/a330neo] In 2014, *The Airline Monitor'*s Ed Greenslet stated that the A330neo would have the advantage of not being designed to fly 8,000 nmi, unlike the A350 and Boeing 787 which were thus less economical on shorter routes, although "the vast majority of long-haul markets is 4,000 nmi or less".
[src:bypass-ratio/a330neo] John Leahy estimated that the A330-900 would have operating costs on par with the 787-9, but would be available at 25% lower capital costs and could reach a production rate of 10 per month after a 7/8 per month rate at the production start.
[src:bypass-ratio/a330neo] Both A330neo variants were expected to have a maximum take-off weight of 242 t.
[src:bypass-ratio/a330neo] The type design was frozen in late 2015.
[src:bypass-ratio/a330neo] On 7 September 2015, Airbus announced that it had begun production of the first A330neo with the construction of its centre wingbox and engine pylon.
[src:bypass-ratio/a330neo] Final assembly of the first aircraft, an A330-900, started in September 2016 at the Airbus Toulouse site with the joining of the wings to the centre fuselage at the station 40.
[src:bypass-ratio/a330neo] In December 2016, the programme schedule slipped by six weeks due to marginal engine development at Rolls-Royce, and launch customer TAP Air Portugal projected its first A330neo would be delivered in March 2018.
[src:bypass-ratio/a330neo] The first aircraft left the paint shop in December 2016, awaiting its engines.
[src:bypass-ratio/a330neo] By April 2017, the Trent 7000s were to be installed later during the summer so that the first flight was delayed until September.
[src:bypass-ratio/a330neo] Due to the delay, TAP Air Portugal was not expected to receive the first A330neo until the end of the first half of 2018, or even in the third quarter.
[src:bypass-ratio/a330neo] The engines were shipped to Airbus in June.
[src:bypass-ratio/a330neo] The aircraft complete with engines showed at Toulouse in September before its first flight.
[src:bypass-ratio/a330neo] Major structures of the first A330-800 were entering production in October 2017: high-lift devices are installed on the wing in Bremen, fuselage sections are built in Hamburg, the centre wing-box in Nantes, titanium engine pylons in Toulouse and sharklet wingtips in Korea.
[src:bypass-ratio/a330neo] Its final assembly started in November 2017, on track for its planned first flight in mid-2018.
[src:bypass-ratio/a330neo] Structural assembly was completed by February 2018, having its flight-test instruments installed and waiting for its engines before its 300h flight-test programme.
[src:bypass-ratio/a330neo] At this time, production aircraft progressed through the final assembly line with the first 'Airspace' cabin interior being fitted.
[src:bypass-ratio/a330neo] A330 production was cut to 50 deliveries in 2019, with more than half of them re-engined A330neos.
[src:bypass-ratio/a330neo] In April 2020, the production rate decreased from 3.5 to 2 per month due to the impact of the COVID-19 pandemic on aviation, and finished planes were stored while waiting for deferred deliveries.
[src:bypass-ratio/a330neo] The A330-900 first flight on 19 October 2017 was a debut of the 1,400 hours flight test campaign involving three prototypes plus the first production aircraft: 1,100 flight hours for the A330-900 and 300 flight hours for the A330-800, targeting mid-2018 EASA and FAA Type Certification.
[src:bypass-ratio/a330neo] It should establish certain maximum operating points and achieve an initial handling qualities assessment including at high angle of attack.
[src:bypass-ratio/a330neo] This first aircraft, MSN1795, was scheduled to perform 600 h and was to be joined the following month by the second, MSN1813, which will fly 500 h, before the third, MSN1819, the first customer aircraft for TAP Portugal with a complete cabin.
[src:bypass-ratio/a330neo] Two flight test engineers and two engine specialists monitored the 60GB per hour output of 1,375 sensors and 98,000 parameters, including strips of microelectromechanical systems to measure aerodynamic pressure distribution across the wing.
[src:bypass-ratio/a330neo] MSN1795 was to undertake simulated icing tests and cold-weather tests in Canada, noise assessment, autoland testing and high angle-of-attack, minimum-unstick checks during rotation with a tail bumper.
[src:bypass-ratio/a330neo] MSN1813 was to test natural icing conditions, assess hot and high conditions in the United Arab Emirates and La Paz, and fly 150h of route-proving; it has rakes and pressure sensors in the engine flows to compare actual thrust with ground bench measurements.
[src:bypass-ratio/a330neo] MSN1819 was to validate the Airspace cabin interior fitting with artificial passengers for ventilation analysis and cabin environment measurements.
[src:bypass-ratio/a330neo] The second test aircraft made its maiden flight on 4 December, to be used to validate aerodynamic & engine performance and airline operations.
[src:bypass-ratio/a330neo] By the end of January 2018, the first logged almost 200h in 58 flights while the second had accumulated nearly 120h in 30 flights.
[src:bypass-ratio/a330neo] Its flight envelope was fully opened including flutter and stall tests to complete powerplant calibration and strake configuration has been frozen.
[src:bypass-ratio/a330neo] Airbus commenced autopilot, autoland and high-speed performance testing, and was to move on to hot- and cold-weather tests, as well as noise and icing tests, over the following three months.
[src:bypass-ratio/a330neo] As of 10 April 2018, the two test aircraft had logged over 200 flights and more than 700 hours, testing −27 °C cold weather, natural icing, crosswind landing, 37 °C and 8,000 ft (2,400 m) hot and high operations.
[src:bypass-ratio/a330neo] The first TAP Air Portugal aircraft made its first flight on 15 May 2018; it joined the two previous test aircraft to check the cabin systems: air conditioning, crew rest, etc.
[src:bypass-ratio/a330neo] It started the final certification step on 18 June: function and reliability tests or route proving, including ETOPS, diversion airport landing, and testing ground handling over 150 flight test hours, as the flight test programme reached 1,000 hours.
[src:bypass-ratio/a330neo] Entry into service was planned for the third quarter of 2018 and ETOPS was to be approved in October for 330min.
[src:bypass-ratio/a330neo] EASA granted the A330-941 type certificate on 26 September 2018, with ETOPS not yet approved.
[src:bypass-ratio/a330neo] ETOPS 180 min was approved on 14 November, restricted to engines with fewer than 500 flight cycles.
[src:bypass-ratio/a330neo] Airbus expects the FAA type certification with 180 min ETOPS by the end of 2018 and 330 min ETOPS in the first half of 2019.
[src:bypass-ratio/a330neo] Beyond-180min ETOPS was approved by the EASA on 24 January 2019.
[src:bypass-ratio/a330neo] The maiden flight of the -800 took place on 6 November 2018; the 4h 4min flight inaugurated a 350h test program aiming for mid-2019 type certification, for delivery in the first half of 2020 to launch operator Kuwait Airways.
[src:bypass-ratio/a330neo] By late March 2019, it was halfway through the 300-hour flight test programme, having completed 44 flights in 149 hours.
[src:bypass-ratio/a330neo] The -800 received EASA type certification with 180-minute ETOPS on 13 February 2020; ETOPS clearance beyond 180 minutes was awarded on 2 April.
[src:bypass-ratio/a330neo] Leased from Avolon, the first A330-900 was delivered to TAP Air Portugal on 26 November 2018, featuring 298 seats: 34 full-flat business, 96 economy plus and 168 economy seats, and to be deployed from Portugal to the Americas and Africa.
[src:bypass-ratio/a330neo] TAP made its first commercial flight on 15 December from Lisbon to São Paulo.
[src:bypass-ratio/a330neo] The airline should receive 15 more A330neos in 2019 and fly the A330-900 from Lisbon to Chicago O'Hare and Washington Dulles from June 2019, both five times a week.
[src:bypass-ratio/a330neo] On the occasion of the 19 October 2017 first flight, an increase to 251 t (553,000 lb) MTOW by mid-2020 was announced, with a few changes to the landing gear and brakes, increasing its range by 700 or 1,000 nmi (1,300 or 1,900 km) compared to the current A330neo or A330ceo.
[src:bypass-ratio/a330neo] The 251 t MTOW was confirmed by Airbus in November 2017.
[src:bypass-ratio/a330neo] Test flights of the 251 t A330-900 started from 28 February 2020.
[src:bypass-ratio/a330neo] Airbus was expecting a short 30–40h test campaign, as multiple tests were conducted with the previous variant adapted to higher weight, including flight performance and noise assessment.
[src:bypass-ratio/a330neo] The heavier structure allows a transpacific range and is balanced by a weight-reduction effort, keeping the same empty weight and payload.
[src:bypass-ratio/a330neo] On 8 October 2020, the 251 t A330-900 was EASA-certified, before introduction by Corsair International.
[src:bypass-ratio/a330neo] Retaining 99% spares commonality, it offers 6 t (13,000 lb) more payload while strengthening the landing-gear and extending the time before overhaul interval from 10 to 12 years.
[src:bypass-ratio/a330neo] On 31 March 2021, Corsair took delivery of the first 251t Airbus A330-900 in a three-class, 352-seat configuration.
[src:bypass-ratio/a330neo] The 251 t A330-800 was certified by EASA in April 2022.
[src:bypass-ratio/a330neo] On 11 June 2025, Airbus planned for 2028 a 253 t (558,000 lb) variant, while a 68,000 lbf (320 kN) thrust rating should be available from 2026.
[src:bypass-ratio/a330neo] The Civil Aviation Administration of China (CAAC) granted the A330neo family its Validation of Type Certificate (VTC) in December 2024.
[src:bypass-ratio/a330neo] Hainan Airlines hinted towards ordering 20 A330-900s with an order for galley parts from Safran in March 2024, while Hong Kong-based Cathay Pacific placed a firm order for 30 A330-900s later that August.
[src:bypass-ratio/a330neo] The A330neo is advertised as having a 12% fuel burn advantage per flight over the older A330 variants.
[src:bypass-ratio/a330neo] This advantage comes from the 11% gain from the Trent 7000 and its larger 112-inch fan, compared to the 97.5-inch Trent 700 engine.
[src:bypass-ratio/a330neo] However, this gain is negated by 3%–2% by additional weight, and 1% due to engine drag, but the sharklets and aero optimization regain 4%, restoring the advantage to 12%.
[src:bypass-ratio/a330neo] Furthermore, fuel consumption per seat is improved by 2% due to the rearranged cabin (Space-Flex and Smart-Lav) with increased seating, offering a 14% fuel burn reduction per seat for the new −900 compared to the previous 235-tonne −300 version.
[src:bypass-ratio/a330neo] The newer 242-tonne −300 is already 2% more efficient.
[src:bypass-ratio/a330neo] Since the fan is enlarged from 97 to 112 in (250 to 280 cm), the nacelles are mounted higher, necessitating extensive CFD analysis to avoid supersonic shock wave interference drag, as is the first slat's dog-tooth.
[src:bypass-ratio/a330neo] The wing twist and belly fairings are tweaked to approach the lowest drag elliptical span-wise pressure distribution changed by the larger sharklets, like the flap track fairings shape to lower form drag.
[src:bypass-ratio/a330neo] Initially based on the largest 242t MTOW A330, Airbus was studying an improvement to 245 t (540,000 lb) MTOW for the A330neo, which would match the figure originally given for the Airbus A350-800 before it was sidelined in favor of the A330neo.
[src:bypass-ratio/a330neo] The redesigned interior, dubbed "Airspace" by Airbus and unveiled in 2016, received larger overhead bins, new ceiling panels with customisable patterns, and updated lighting.
[src:bypass-ratio/a330neo] Many design elements were incorporated from the A350.
[src:bypass-ratio/a330neo] The cockpit windows feature a black "mask" outline, similar to the A350.
[src:bypass-ratio/a330neo] Candidate engines included variants of Rolls-Royce's Trent 1000 and General Electric's GEnx-1B.
[src:bypass-ratio/a330neo] Both engine makers were reportedly interested in winning an exclusive deal should a re-engined A330 be offered.
[src:bypass-ratio/a330neo] The Trent 1000 TEN (Thrust, Efficiency, New Technology) engine was under development for the 787-10, but Rolls-Royce intended to offer a broad power range.
[src:bypass-ratio/a330neo] The A330neo uses the Rolls-Royce Trent 7000 engine, which is an electronic controlled bleed air variant of the Trent 1000 used on the Boeing 787-10.
[src:bypass-ratio/a330neo] It will have a 112 in (284 cm) diameter fan and a 10:1 bypass ratio.
[src:bypass-ratio/a330neo] The Trent is the exclusive powerplant, as Rolls-Royce offered better terms to obtain exclusivity.
[src:bypass-ratio/a330neo] The decision to offer the aircraft with only one engine option is not unique to Airbus; the Boeing 777X will come equipped exclusively with General Electric GE9X engines, after Rolls-Royce made a bid with its Advance configuration but was not selected.
[src:bypass-ratio/a330neo] The A330-800 retains the fuselage length of the A330-200, but can seat six more passengers (for a total of 252) with an optimised cabin featuring 18-inch-wide economy seats.
[src:bypass-ratio/a330neo] As the variants share 99% commonality, developing the smaller -800 has a negligible extra cost.
[src:bypass-ratio/a330neo] After the first flight of the -900 on 19 October 2017, Hawaiian Airlines (then the only customer for the -800) considered changing its order to six -800s, seeking best to fit its current network to Asia and North America whilst allowing for future growth, possibly to Europe.
[src:bypass-ratio/a330neo] In contrast, the -200 commanded 40% of the CEO deliveries: its range advantage has eroded with the increased capabilities of the -900, and although it offers lower fuel use per trip, fuel use per seat is higher.
[src:bypass-ratio/a330neo] As of 2017, demand for the -800 was limited by low fuel prices and the -200s it might replace after 2020 were still young (nine years on average).
[src:bypass-ratio/a330neo] The Boeing 767-300s that the -800 might replace are 15 years older, and while Boeing considered relaunching production of the 767-300ER, mainly as an interim for American and United Airlines, this was complicated by a 30-year-old design including obsolete cabin amenities.
[src:bypass-ratio/a330neo] At this time, Boeing intended to launch its New Midsize Airplane no earlier than 2027, affording Airbus opportunities with the 95 operators of the A330ceo.
[src:bypass-ratio/a330neo] Production of the -800 beyond the prototype was in doubt, as Hawaiian was choosing between the Airbus A350-900 and the Boeing 787-8/9.
[src:bypass-ratio/a330neo] In February 2018, Hawaiian was thought to be cancelling its order for six A330-800s, replacing them with Boeing 787-9s priced at less than $100–115m, close to their production cost of $80–90m, while Boeing Capital released Hawaiian from three 767-300ER leases well in advance.
[src:bypass-ratio/a330neo] Hawaiian denied that the order for the A330-800 had been cancelled, but did not dismiss a new deal with Boeing.
[src:bypass-ratio/a330neo] In March 2018, Hawaiian confirmed the cancellation of its order for six A330-800s and ordered ten B787-9s instead.
[src:bypass-ratio/a330neo] Airbus says it was "simply undercut in price".
[src:bypass-ratio/a330neo] In July 2018, a new memorandum of understanding from Uganda Airlines for two -800s revived interest in the shorter variant.
[src:bypass-ratio/a330neo] On 8 April 2019, Uganda National Airlines Company firmed up its order for two -800s.
[src:bypass-ratio/a330neo] Airbus could limit its MTOW to 200 t (440,000 lb) and derate its engines to 68,000 lbf (300,000 N) to optimise for the shorter routes to be targeted by the Boeing NMA, with the A321XLR tackling the lower end of the same niche.
[src:bypass-ratio/a330neo] The A330-800 received EASA type certification on 13 February 2020.
[src:bypass-ratio/a330neo] The first aircraft, configured with 226 seats including 23 in business class, was to be delivered to Kuwait Airways in March, but the airline postponed delivery until the third quarter of 2020 amid the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:bypass-ratio/a330neo] On 29 October, the first two A330-800s were delivered to Kuwait Airways; the airline had six more -800s on order but subsequently decided to switch to the -900, becoming the first airline to operate both variants.
[src:bypass-ratio/a330neo] The A330-800 then operated its first revenue flight on 20 November, flying the short distance between Kuwait and Dubai.
[src:bypass-ratio/a330neo] Uganda Airlines received their first A330-800 on 21 December, with the second unit expected in January 2021.
[src:bypass-ratio/a330neo] Air Greenland took delivery of its only A330-800, named *Tuukkaq*, on 6 December 2022 and entered service on 19 December 2022 as a replacement for their Airbus A330-200, *Norsaq*.
[src:bypass-ratio/a330neo] As of March 2024, there are only seven A330-800s in revenue service with just three operators; Kuwait Airways is the largest operator with four aircraft in its fleet.
[src:bypass-ratio/a330neo] Garuda Indonesia was the fourth airline to order four A330-800s but the order was later cancelled.
[src:bypass-ratio/a330neo] The A330-900 retains the fuselage length of the A330-300 and the similarly sized four-engined A340-300.
[src:bypass-ratio/a330neo] Cabin optimisation allows ten additional seats on the A330-900 (310 passengers) with 18-inch-wide economy seats.
[src:bypass-ratio/a330neo] Delta expects a 20 percent reduction in operating cost per seat over the Boeing 767-300ER aircraft it replaces.
[src:bypass-ratio/a330neo] Further reconfiguration of cabin facilities enables the –900 to seat up to 460 passengers in an all-economy layout.
[src:bypass-ratio/a330neo] This exceeds the existing 440-seat maximum exit limit allowed by the type certificate, and requires a modification of the Type-A exit doors to meet emergency exit requirements.
[src:bypass-ratio/a330neo] In November 2019, maximum accommodation increased to 460 seats, through the installation of new 'Type-A+' exits, with a dual-lane evacuation slide.
[src:bypass-ratio/a330neo] Amazon Air and UPS Airlines pushed for a freighter version, stretching the A330-900 to carry more cargo over a shorter range, but it competes with the cheaper option of converting readily available retired passenger 767 and A330 aircraft.
[src:bypass-ratio/a330neo] Development costs for the proposed freighter would be lower than for a new program, as much of the engineering has already been done for the A330-200F.
[src:bypass-ratio/a330neo] Airbus formally launched the tanker variant of the A330neo, dubbed as the A330 MRTT+, at the 2024 Farnborough International Airshow.
[src:bypass-ratio/a330neo] The A330 MRTT+ is based on the A330-800 and is intended to replace the A330 MRTT.
[src:bypass-ratio/a330neo] The A330 MRTT+ also retains the 111,000 kg (245,000 lb) fuel capacity of the A330 MRTT.
[src:bypass-ratio/a330neo] Airbus plans to deliver the first A330 MRTT+ in 2029.
[src:bypass-ratio/a330neo] The launch customer is expected to be the Royal Thai Air Force.
[src:bypass-ratio/a330neo] Airbus launched the business version of the A330neo, known as the ACJ330neo.
[src:bypass-ratio/a330neo] It can carry a maximum of 25 passengers and can fly up to 10,400 nautical miles in 21 hours without refueling.
[src:bypass-ratio/a330neo] There are two versions of the business jet which are the ACJ330-800 and the ACJ330-900 and there are four cabin outfits.
[src:bypass-ratio/a330neo] Below is a list of major differences between the A330neo variants.
[src:bypass-ratio/a330neo] There are 195 aircraft in service with 25 operators as of May 2026.
[src:bypass-ratio/a330neo] The five largest operators of A330neo are Delta Air Lines (39), TAP Air Portugal (19), Condor (18), ITA Airways (16) and Cebu Pacific (14).
[src:bypass-ratio/a330neo] On 11 April 2023, Airbus delivered the 100th A330neo, an A330-900, to German airline Condor Flugdienst GmbH, which would lease it from AerCap.
[src:bypass-ratio/a330neo] At that time, the A330neo Family flew in the liveries of 22 airlines on over 200 routes and destinations worldwide.
[src:bypass-ratio/a330neo] They have close economics but the A330neo costs up to $30m less, according to another publication.
[src:bypass-ratio/a330neo] An A330-900 is worth $115 million in 2018, while a new B787-9 valuation is $145 million, up from $135 million in 2014, but it may have been sold for $110–15 million to prevent A330neo sales.
[src:bypass-ratio/a330neo] Between the 2004 launch of the Dreamliner and the A330neo launch in 2014, the market was split almost equally between both, with between 900 and 920 A330ceos sold against 950 to 1,000 787-8/9s.
[src:bypass-ratio/a330neo] Between 2014 and the neo first flight in October 2017, the A330/A330neo had 440 orders (excluding freighters) compared to 272 for the 787-8/9 (excluding the -10), or since the 787 launch, 1211 A330ceo/neos compared to 1106 787-8/9s.
[src:bypass-ratio/a330neo] Teal Group's Richard Aboulafia believes that the A330neo should dominate the lower range and lower capacity end of the twin aisle market because the 787-8 has the high operating economics and unit price associated with its 8,000-nm range.
[src:bypass-ratio/a330neo] Flightglobal Ascend Consultancy forecast 600 deliveries including 10% of -800 variants, less optimistic than Airbus's 1,000.
[src:bypass-ratio/a330neo] At entry into service in 2018, sales were disappointing and A330 production was to be cut to 50 in 2019 down from 67 in 2017: while it was the widebody with the largest operator base with 1,390 deliveries since 1993, the fleet was still very young with only 46 aircraft retired.
[src:bypass-ratio/a330neo] Airbus believed A330 operators would start fleet renewal beginning in 2020.
[src:bypass-ratio/a330neo] With the exception of Delta, industry-leading airlines preferred the Boeing 787.
[src:bypass-ratio/a330neo] Between January 2014 and November 2019, the A330/A330neo had 477 net orders (net of cancellations) compared to a total of 407 for all three variants of the 787.
[src:bypass-ratio/a330neo] The A330neo program was the best-selling Airbus widebody over the same period.
[src:bypass-ratio/a330neo] Airbus believes there is potential for the A330neo in the growing long-haul, low-cost carrier sector.
[src:bypass-ratio/a330neo] While Airbus expected a market for over 1,000 A330neos, one pessimistic forecast reported in 2018 came in as low as 400 sales, in that the A330neo was late to the market and fuel prices had declined markedly over the years, reducing demand.
[src:bypass-ratio/a330neo] As of June 2018, 19% of A330 operators also operate the Boeing 787.
[src:bypass-ratio/a330neo] Leeham News argued that the A330-800 does not fully cover the upper end of Boeing's studied New Midsize Airplane market, while also describing the A330-800 as a cost-effective entry for Airbus into the upper end of the middle of the market.
[src:bypass-ratio/a330neo] In May 2019, Airbus's chief commercial officer made clear the company has a “rock”, the A321neo, and a “hard place”, the A330-800, for any airframer intending to bring a new airplane into the middle of the market at a time when Boeing was mired in the 737 MAX crisis.
[src:bypass-ratio/accessory-drive] The **accessory drive** is a gearbox that forms part of a gas turbine engine.
[src:bypass-ratio/accessory-drive] Although not part of the engine's core, it drives the accessories – such as generators, pumps for fuel and lubrication oil, air compressors, hydraulic pumps and engine starters – that are otherwise essential for the operation of the engine or the aircraft on which it is mounted.
[src:bypass-ratio/accessory-drive] Accessory drives on large engines handle between 400–500 hp.
[src:bypass-ratio/accessory-drive] Power for the accessory drive is taken from the central shaft linking the turbine and compressor sections of the engine.
[src:bypass-ratio/accessory-drive] This requires an internal gearbox that couples the drive to a radial driveshaft or *towershaft* that drives an external gearbox.
[src:bypass-ratio/accessory-drive] The design of the internal gearbox is complicated by the heat and small space available in which to connect the driveshaft.
[src:bypass-ratio/accessory-drive] It is usually placed between the compressor outlet and the combustor.
[src:bypass-ratio/accessory-drive] In turboprops or designs with centrifugal compressors, it may be placed ahead of the compressor.
[src:bypass-ratio/accessory-drive] For two-shaft designs, an accessory drive will be taken from the high-pressure shaft, i.e. the outer and shorter of the two concentric shafts.
[src:bypass-ratio/accessory-drive] This shaft comes up to speed more quickly when the engine is started.
[src:bypass-ratio/accessory-drive] The drive and accessory gearboxes may also be split in two, one driven from each engine shaft, so as to distribute their loads.
[src:bypass-ratio/accessory-drive] The engine-critical systems, including the starter drive, are arranged on the high-pressure shaft, with aircraft systems on the low-pressure shaft.
[src:bypass-ratio/accessory-drive] The high-pressure shaft also rotates faster than the low-pressure shaft, which may influence the distribution of accessories.
[src:bypass-ratio/accessory-drive] To make the best use of the limited space for the driveshaft and internal gearbox, the driveshaft runs at high speed, thus allowing it to be of small diameter.
[src:bypass-ratio/accessory-drive] This reduces the disruption to the airflow and the size of the hollow fairing that encloses it.
[src:bypass-ratio/accessory-drive] If it is not possible to arrange a single straight path for the driveshaft, it may be arranged in two sections and linked by an intermediate gearbox.
[src:bypass-ratio/accessory-drive] This is most commonly required for high-bypass turbofans with large diameter fans.
[src:bypass-ratio/accessory-drive] The packaging of an engine within its nacelle is a complicated task.
[src:bypass-ratio/accessory-drive] The accessory drive is usually arranged as a curved casing, so that the various accessories are mounted close to the engine.
[src:bypass-ratio/accessory-drive] The casing is a pair of light alloy castings.
[src:bypass-ratio/accessory-drive] Separate machined mounting pads are provided for each accessory.
[src:bypass-ratio/accessory-drive] The drive within the casing is provided by a train of spur gears.
[src:bypass-ratio/accessory-drive] Accessories are arranged on both sides of the driveshaft entry, in reducing order of their speed.
[src:bypass-ratio/accessory-drive] The gears are usually plain spur gears, running in roller bearings.
[src:bypass-ratio/accessory-drive] Idler gears are commonly used between them, to increase the spacing between accessories.
[src:bypass-ratio/accessory-drive] Helical gears are sometimes used for the high-torque drives, typically the starter, as these give smoother running.
[src:bypass-ratio/accessory-drive] However helical gears also generate an end-thrust, which then requires a more complicated thrust bearing to support them.
[src:bypass-ratio/accessory-drive] The complexity of an accessory drive and its gears is so great that they were used as a theme by the anthropomorphic illustrator Boris Artzybasheff in advertising for the Avco Lycoming company, who were making drive gearboxes for the Westinghouse J40 engine.
[src:bypass-ratio/accessory-drive] In some engines, bleed air is also tapped to provide power for accessories, as well as a mechanical shaft drive.
[src:bypass-ratio/accessory-drive] Bleed air is particularly useful when a source of compressed air is specifically needed, either to pressurise cabin air, or as a supply of cooling air to other components (to avoid excess heat, this is taken for a low-pressure tapping, or from the LP compressor of a two-shaft engine).
[src:bypass-ratio/accessory-drive] One important use for bleed air is for cross-starting of other engines in a multi-engine aircraft.
[src:bypass-ratio/accessory-drive] Additional facilities are provided for a centrifugal oil breather, to separate the drive lubricating oil from the overboard breather air vent.
[src:bypass-ratio/accessory-drive] Also access for hand-turning the engine, during ground maintenance.
[src:bypass-ratio/aero-l-159-alca] The **Aero L-159 ALCA** is a subsonic light combat aircraft and advanced trainer developed in the single-seat L-159A and two-seat L-159B versions, respectively, produced in the Czech Republic by Aero Vodochody.
[src:bypass-ratio/aero-l-159-alca] It was derived from the Aero L-59 Super Albatros trainer, which was in turn developed from the Aero L-39 Albatros series.
[src:bypass-ratio/aero-l-159-alca] Development of the L-159 started in 1993 as an initiative to replace various Soviet-era fighter aircraft with a modern Czech-built equivalent; it was decided against pursuing a clean-sheet design to avoid excessive costs.
[src:bypass-ratio/aero-l-159-alca] Development was supported by the Czech government, which ordered 72 L-159A single-seat aircraft for roughly 50 billion CZK to equip the Czech Air Force.
[src:bypass-ratio/aero-l-159-alca] In 1998, the Boeing Company became a strategic partner in both the project and Aero Vodochody itself.
[src:bypass-ratio/aero-l-159-alca] On 4 August 1997, the L-159 performed its maiden flight; on 10 April 2000, the first production aircraft was delivered to the Czech Air Force.
[src:bypass-ratio/aero-l-159-alca] Further development of the type proceeded, particularly of the twin-seat L-159 models.
[src:bypass-ratio/aero-l-159-alca] In 2003, the Czech fleet of 72 L-159A aircraft was reduced to 24 due to budget constraints.
[src:bypass-ratio/aero-l-159-alca] Following several years of storage, the Czech government has re-sold most of the redundant aircraft to both military and civilian operators, namely the Iraqi Air Force and Draken International.
[src:bypass-ratio/aero-l-159-alca] The L-159 has seen active combat use by the Iraqi Air Force against Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant (ISIS) insurgents in the country.
[src:bypass-ratio/aero-l-159-alca] In Draken's service, the L-159 (colloquially known as "Honey Badger") has been employed as an aggressor aircraft for pilot training.
[src:bypass-ratio/aero-l-159-alca] Since 2007, six L-159A aircraft have been rebuilt into T1 trainer derivatives.
[src:bypass-ratio/aero-l-159-alca] During 2017, Aero Vodochody formally restarted production of the type, and unveiled a newly built L-159T1 for the Iraqi Air Force; furthermore, the Czech Air Force was in the process of acquiring L-159T2 two-seaters.
[src:bypass-ratio/aero-l-159-alca] Immediately after the 1989 Velvet Revolution, the president of Czechoslovakia Václav Havel declared a demobilisation of the Czechoslovak defence industry.
[src:bypass-ratio/aero-l-159-alca] Nevertheless, after the dissolution of the Soviet Union in 1991, the Czech company Aero Vodochody continued developing the basic L-39 Albatros design with a view toward greater export.
[src:bypass-ratio/aero-l-159-alca] The resulting L-39MS, later designed as L-59 Super Albatros, featured a more powerful turbofan engine, advanced avionics, and has been bought in quantity by Egypt and Tunisia.
[src:bypass-ratio/aero-l-159-alca] In 1993, a group of Czech military experts launched a project to produce a modern domestic fighter to replace the obsolete Soviet aircraft.
[src:bypass-ratio/aero-l-159-alca] Since the proposed Aero L-X supersonic fighter development proved to be financially demanding (up to US$2 billion), the less costly L-159 subsonic attack aircraft, derived from the L-39 Albatros, was approved for procurement instead.
[src:bypass-ratio/aero-l-159-alca] During 1995, the Czech government placed a large order for 72 L-159A single-seat aircraft at a cost around 50 billion CZK.
[src:bypass-ratio/aero-l-159-alca] The number of aircraft to be delivered was based upon the size of the Czech Air Force at that time, taking into account the necessity to replace MiG-23BN and Su-22 fighter-bombers and Su-25 attack aircraft.
[src:bypass-ratio/aero-l-159-alca] Due to the cost of the project, the Czech government decided that a strategic partner, the Boeing Company, would be invited to collaborate with Aero Vodochody in the venture during May 1998.
[src:bypass-ratio/aero-l-159-alca] The maiden flight of the first L-159 prototype (5831, "376 white") occurred on 2 August 1997 with a two-seat version.
[src:bypass-ratio/aero-l-159-alca] On 18 August 1998, the single-seat L-159A prototype (5832, "356 white") first flew; it was completed to Czech customer specifications.
[src:bypass-ratio/aero-l-159-alca] On 10 April 2000, the first delivery of the L-159A took place to the Czech Air Force.
[src:bypass-ratio/aero-l-159-alca] Prototype (6073) of the two-seat L-159B variant first flew on 1 June 2002.
[src:bypass-ratio/aero-l-159-alca] During October 2004, the Czech government announced that Aero Vodochody was to be privatised, and Boeing decided to withdraw from involvement in both the L-159 and the overall company.
[src:bypass-ratio/aero-l-159-alca] During October 2006, Aero Vodochody was sold to Penta Investments.
[src:bypass-ratio/aero-l-159-alca] In 2009, Aero Vodochody selected *V-Dot Systems* (split off from Boeing) as the L-159 avionics integrator.
[src:bypass-ratio/aero-l-159-alca] V-Dot will replace the Honeywell multi-function displays (MFD) and upgrade the mission processors to support new functions.
[src:bypass-ratio/aero-l-159-alca] On 31 March 2017, following a 13-year stoppage in L-159 production after the delivery of the final Czech Air Force example, Aero Vodochody held a ceremony to mark the resumption of manufacturing; a new-build L-159 destined for the Iraqi Air Force was present.
[src:bypass-ratio/aero-l-159-alca] This batch of production aircraft featured several improvements, such as the use of a wet wing and increased endurance; further enhancements were also being worked on at that time.
[src:bypass-ratio/aero-l-159-alca] The company reportedly negotiated with Argentina on the topic of the L-159, which reportedly may have included the establishment of an assembly line in the country.
[src:bypass-ratio/aero-l-159-alca] The L-159 ALCA is designed for the principal role of light combat aircraft (single-seat L-159A variant) or light attack jet and advanced/lead-in fighter trainer (two-seat L-159B and T variants).
[src:bypass-ratio/aero-l-159-alca] Design of the L-159 was derived from the L-39/59 in terms of aerodynamic configuration but a number of changes were made to improve its combat capabilities.
[src:bypass-ratio/aero-l-159-alca] These include strengthening of the airframe, reinforcing of the cockpit with composite and ceramic ballistic armour and enlargement of the aircraft's nose to accommodate the radar.
[src:bypass-ratio/aero-l-159-alca] Compared to the L-59, the number of underwing pylons was increased from four to six, and a new hardpoint under the fuselage was added instead of a GSh-23L cannon.
[src:bypass-ratio/aero-l-159-alca] The aircraft is powered by the non-afterburning Honeywell/ITEC F124-GA-100 turbofan engine with a maximum thrust of 28 kN.
[src:bypass-ratio/aero-l-159-alca] Almost 2,000 litres of fuel are stored in eight internal tanks (six in the fuselage, two at the wingtips) with up to four external drop tanks (two 500 L and two 350 L tanks) carried under the wings.
[src:bypass-ratio/aero-l-159-alca] The lightly armoured cockpit is equipped with a VS-2B ejection seat capable of catapulting the pilot at a zero flight level and zero speed.
[src:bypass-ratio/aero-l-159-alca] The aircraft's avionics, based on the MIL-STD-1553 databus, include Selex Navigation and Attack Suite, Ring Laser Gyro based Inertial Navigation System (INS) and Global Positioning System (GPS).
[src:bypass-ratio/aero-l-159-alca] Flight data are displayed both on the FV-3000 head-up display (HUD) and two multi-function displays (MFD).
[src:bypass-ratio/aero-l-159-alca] Communications are provided by a pair of Collins ARC-182 transceivers.
[src:bypass-ratio/aero-l-159-alca] Self-protection of the L-159 is ensured by the Sky Guardian 200 radar warning receiver (RWR) and the Vinten Vicon 78 Series 455 chaff and flare dispenser.
[src:bypass-ratio/aero-l-159-alca] L-159A and T2 variants are equipped with the Italian FIAR Grifo L multi-mode Doppler radar for all-weather, day and night operations.
[src:bypass-ratio/aero-l-159-alca] All variants of L-159 are equipped with a total of seven hardpoints (one under-fuselage and six under-wing mountings), capable of carrying external loads up to 2,340 kg.
[src:bypass-ratio/aero-l-159-alca] The aircraft can be equipped with a variety of weapons ranging from unguided bombs and rocket pods to air-to-ground and air-to-air guided missiles or with special devices to conduct aerial reconnaissance or electronic warfare.
[src:bypass-ratio/aero-l-159-alca] For example, it is capable of carrying advanced targeting pods including the AN/AAQ-28(V) LITENING.
[src:bypass-ratio/aero-l-159-alca] The Czech Air Force is the primary operator of the L-159.
[src:bypass-ratio/aero-l-159-alca] During 1995, the Czech government ordered 72 aircraft, but after review, opted to reduce the fleet size to 24 L-159s, which received the latest avionics upgrades, while the remaining aircraft were placed into long-term storage.
[src:bypass-ratio/aero-l-159-alca] By 2016, the Czech Air Force had 16 L-159A and 5 L-159T1 aircraft in service.
[src:bypass-ratio/aero-l-159-alca] On 1 June 2016, Aero Vodochody received an order to upgrade an initial batch of 16 Czech Air Force L-159s.
[src:bypass-ratio/aero-l-159-alca] On 15 October 2012, it was announced that Iraq had agreed to purchase 28 L-159s from the Czech government.
[src:bypass-ratio/aero-l-159-alca] During early 2015, Iraq signed a deal for 14 L-159 aircraft, comprising 12 L-159As and two L-159T1s, for the Iraqi Air Force.
[src:bypass-ratio/aero-l-159-alca] This sale was politically controversial in the United Kingdom, as it necessitated the lifting of a long-standing ban on the export of British radar technology to Iraq.
[src:bypass-ratio/aero-l-159-alca] The first two Czech L-159s were delivered to Iraq on 5 November 2015.
[src:bypass-ratio/aero-l-159-alca] In May 2016, numerous Iraqi L-159s participated in attacks upon positions held by Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant (ISIL) insurgents in the city of Fallujah.
[src:bypass-ratio/aero-l-159-alca] During October and November 2016, L-159 aircraft operated by Squadron No.
[src:bypass-ratio/aero-l-159-alca] 115 were deployed in the battle against ISIL forces at the Southern outskirts of Mosul.
[src:bypass-ratio/aero-l-159-alca] As the threat posed by ISIS diminished in Iraq, the L-159s were placed into temporary storage around 2017 or 2018.
[src:bypass-ratio/aero-l-159-alca] During February 2022, it was announced that the Iraqi L159s had been brought back into active service, although they were only capable of limited operations initially.
[src:bypass-ratio/aero-l-159-alca] It had reportedly been used in multiple strikes against insurgents in ISIL hideouts in the Hamrin Mountains of Diyala province during late 2021.
[src:bypass-ratio/aero-l-159-alca] During early 2022, Iraq has been in contact with Aero Vodochody on the topic of modernising its L-159 fleet.
[src:bypass-ratio/aero-l-159-alca] As of March 2023 an Iraqi L159 was photographed carrying the Turkish Aselpod reconnaissance, surveillance and targeting pod.
[src:bypass-ratio/aero-l-159-alca] In 2009, EADS-CASA of Spain exchanged with the CzAF four CASA C-295 for three L-159As, two L-159T1s and 130 million Euros.
[src:bypass-ratio/aero-l-159-alca] Later the two L-159T1s were returned by EADS-CASA to the Czech Republic as compensation for the C-295M not meeting the counter measures requirements of the CzAF at the time of delivery.
[src:bypass-ratio/aero-l-159-alca] This problem has been solved by EADS-CASA three years later and the remaining three L-159As resold by EADS-CASA to Lewis Fighter Fleet LLC.
[src:bypass-ratio/aero-l-159-alca] During 2014, it was announced that Draken International Inc., a civilian American company that cooperates with the US military for pilot training, was in the process of acquiring 21 ex-Czech Air Force L-159s.
[src:bypass-ratio/aero-l-159-alca] The deal made Draken International into the world's largest private air force.
[src:bypass-ratio/aero-l-159-alca] Aero Vodochody handed over the first L-159 aircraft to the company on 30 September 2015.
[src:bypass-ratio/aero-l-159-alca] Draken International has secured contacts with both the United States Air Force and the Royal Air Force to use its L-159s as aggressor aircraft for pilot training.
[src:bypass-ratio/aero-l-159-alca] A separate company, Lewis Fighter Fleet LLC, also operates three L-159As for its own purposes.
[src:bypass-ratio/aero-l-159-alca] These aircraft, which were formerly owned by EADS-CASA, were acquired by the firm in July 2013.
[src:bypass-ratio/aero-l-159-alca] The L-159A ALCA is a single-seat light multi-role combat aircraft designed for a variety of air-to-air, air-to-ground and reconnaissance missions.
[src:bypass-ratio/aero-l-159-alca] The aircraft is equipped with a multi-mode Doppler Grifo-L radar (a variant of the Grifo-F x-band multi-mode, pulse-doppler radar), for all-weather, day and night operations.
[src:bypass-ratio/aero-l-159-alca] It can carry a wide range of NATO standard stores including air-to-air and air-to-ground missiles and laser guided bombs.
[src:bypass-ratio/aero-l-159-alca] The L-159A is in operational service with the Czech and Iraqi air forces.
[src:bypass-ratio/aero-l-159-alca] There are two different configurations being used by the Czech Air Force – using the Honeywell 4x4 inch MFDs or the Vdot 5x6.7 inch MFDs.
[src:bypass-ratio/aero-l-159-alca] Avionic upgrades are designed and developed by V-Dot Systems Inc.
[src:bypass-ratio/aero-l-159-alca] The L-159E ALCA is the export designation of L-159A in service with Draken International.
[src:bypass-ratio/aero-l-159-alca] Combat-capable variant first unveiled at the Farnborough Airshow on 16 July 2018.
[src:bypass-ratio/aero-l-159-alca] Developed in collaboration with Israel Aerospace Industries and powered by a Honeywell F124-GA-100 engine.
[src:bypass-ratio/aero-l-159-alca] Air Force Light Attack/Armed Reconnaissance program.
[src:bypass-ratio/aero-l-159-alca] The L-159B, also known as L-159B Albatros II, is a two-seat version primarily designed for Advanced and Operational/Lead-In Fighter Training.
[src:bypass-ratio/aero-l-159-alca] The L-159B configuration can also be tailored to customer specific requirements and adapted to needs of basic training as well as combat missions including air-to-ground, patrol and reconnaissance missions.
[src:bypass-ratio/aero-l-159-alca] On 23 July 2002, the Czech military signed a letter of intent on acquisition of the first two L-159B aircraft.
[src:bypass-ratio/aero-l-159-alca] However, due to the budget constraints the trade did not materialize.
[src:bypass-ratio/aero-l-159-alca] The only prototype has been rebuilt by Aero Vodochody into **L-159T2X** demonstrator.
[src:bypass-ratio/aero-l-159-alca] The aircraft's designation was changed on 14 December 2015.
[src:bypass-ratio/aero-l-159-alca] The L-159T1 is a two-seat trainer derivative used by the Czech and Iraqi Air Force.
[src:bypass-ratio/aero-l-159-alca] All L-159T1s (excluding one newly built L-159T1 for the Iraqi Air Force) are modified L-159A airframes taken from storage.
[src:bypass-ratio/aero-l-159-alca] Unlike L-159A, they have just one MFD in each cockpit and no radar.
[src:bypass-ratio/aero-l-159-alca] L-159T1 S/N 6069 made its first flight on 8 March 2007 and the first batch of four aircraft was handed over to the Czech Air Force on 23 November 2007.
[src:bypass-ratio/aero-l-159-alca] Another two aircraft were delivered in August and December 2010, respectively.
[src:bypass-ratio/aero-l-159-alca] L-159T1 S/N 6069 was transferred to Aero Vodochody on 30 June 2015 as a part of the Iraqi contract which included handover of four actively used aircraft – three L-159A and one L-159T1 – to the Iraqi Air Force.
[src:bypass-ratio/aero-l-159-alca] Prototype L-159T1+ S/N 6067 (manufactured as L-159A in 2003 and converted to L-159T1 in 2007) was unveiled by Aero Vodochody in March 2017.
[src:bypass-ratio/aero-l-159-alca] L-159T1+ aircraft are characterized by an upgraded mission system, avionics and newly installed Grifo-L radar, offering the same combat capability as the single-seat L-159A.
[src:bypass-ratio/aero-l-159-alca] The T1+ modernization of 4 Czech Air Force L-159T1 is scheduled to be completed in December 2019.
[src:bypass-ratio/aero-l-159-alca] The L-159T2 is a two-seat trainer with full combat capability converted from stored L-159A airframes.
[src:bypass-ratio/aero-l-159-alca] Compared to the L-159T1, it has a higher proportion of newly manufactured components and a Grifo-L radar installed.
[src:bypass-ratio/aero-l-159-alca] Instead of mirroring the instruments to the rear seat, the new two-seater will have independent instruments interchangeable with the L-159A while using the same software configuration.
[src:bypass-ratio/aero-l-159-alca] The Czech Air Force has ordered 3 L-159T2 aircraft scheduled to be delivered in November 2018.
[src:bypass-ratio/aero-l-159-alca] On 11 May 2023, Czech President Petr Pavel, in a radio interview, offered the L-159 to Ukraine.
[src:bypass-ratio/aero-l-159-alca] Subject to a decision by the Czech government, President Pavel said “It is worth considering whether we could provide Ukraine with our L-159 aircraft.
[src:bypass-ratio/aero-l-159-alca] As direct combat support aircraft, (the planes) could also help Ukraine significantly in the counteroffensive”.
[src:bypass-ratio/aero-l-159-alca] They also carry an array of western weapons such as: “AIM-9 Sidewinder missiles, AIM-120 AMRAAM, AGM-65 Maverick, and GBU-12 Paveway II and GBU-16 Paveway II laser-guided bombs.” They also are a Czech aircraft, approval from other countries is not required.
[src:bypass-ratio/aero-l-159-alca] It is also an upgrade from the Aero L-39 Albatros that the Ukraine Air Force uses.
[src:bypass-ratio/aero-l-159-alca] On 16 January 2026, Czech president Petr Pavel has pledged to provide Ukraine with “medium combat planes which are highly effective in fighting drones”—this likely refers to the L-159 light fighter jet.
[src:bypass-ratio/afterburner] An **afterburner** (or **reheat** in British English) is an additional combustion component used on some jet engines, mostly those on military supersonic aircraft.
[src:bypass-ratio/afterburner] Its purpose is to increase thrust, usually for supersonic flight, takeoff, and combat.
[src:bypass-ratio/afterburner] The afterburning process injects additional fuel into a combustor ("burner") in the jet pipe behind (i.e., "after") the turbine, "reheating" the exhaust gas.
[src:bypass-ratio/afterburner] Afterburning significantly increases thrust and is used as an alternative to a larger, heavier engine.
[src:bypass-ratio/afterburner] However, it increases fuel consumption and decreases fuel efficiency, which limits its use to short periods.
[src:bypass-ratio/afterburner] This aircraft application of "reheat" contrasts with the meaning and implementation of "reheat" applicable to gas turbines driving electrical generators and which reduces fuel consumption.
[src:bypass-ratio/afterburner] Jet engines are referred to as operating *wet* when afterburning and *dry* when not.
[src:bypass-ratio/afterburner] An engine producing maximum thrust wet is at *maximum power,* while an engine producing maximum thrust dry is at *military power*.
[src:bypass-ratio/afterburner] The first jet engine with after-burner was the E variant of the Jumo 004.
[src:bypass-ratio/afterburner] Jet-engine thrust is an application of Newton's reaction principle, in which the engine generates thrust because it increases the momentum of the air passing through it.
[src:bypass-ratio/afterburner] Thrust depends on two things: the velocity of the exhaust gas and the mass of the gas exiting the nozzle.
[src:bypass-ratio/afterburner] A jet engine can produce more thrust by either accelerating the gas to a higher velocity or ejecting a greater mass of gas from the engine.
[src:bypass-ratio/afterburner] Designing a basic turbojet engine around the second principle produces the turbofan engine, which creates slower gas, but more of it.
[src:bypass-ratio/afterburner] Turbofans are highly fuel efficient and can deliver high thrust for long periods of time, but the design tradeoff is a large size relative to the power output.
[src:bypass-ratio/afterburner] Generating increased power with a more compact engine for short periods can be achieved using an afterburner.
[src:bypass-ratio/afterburner] The afterburner increases thrust primarily by accelerating the exhaust gas to a higher velocity.
[src:bypass-ratio/afterburner] The following values and parameters are for an early jet engine, the Pratt & Whitney J57, stationary on the runway, and illustrate the high values of afterburner fuel flow, gas temperature and thrust compared to those for the engine operating within the temperature limitations for its turbine.
[src:bypass-ratio/afterburner] The highest temperature in the engine (about 3,700 °F (2,040 °C) occurs in the combustion chamber, where fuel is burned (at an approximate rate of 8,520 lb/h (3,860 kg/h)) in a relatively small proportion of the air entering the engine.
[src:bypass-ratio/afterburner] The combustion products have to be diluted with air from the compressor to bring the gas temperature down to a specific value, known as the Turbine Entry Temperature (TET) (1,570 °F (850 °C)), which gives the turbine an acceptable life.
[src:bypass-ratio/afterburner] Having to reduce the temperature of the combustion products by a large amount is one of the primary limitations on how much thrust can be generated (10,200 lbf (45,000 N)).
[src:bypass-ratio/afterburner] The gas temperature decreases as it passes through the turbine (to 1,013 °F (545 °C)).
[src:bypass-ratio/afterburner] The afterburner combustor reheats the gas, but to a much higher temperature (2,540 °F (1,390 °C)) than the TET (1,570 °F (850 °C)).
[src:bypass-ratio/afterburner] As a result of the temperature rise in the afterburner combustor, the gas is accelerated, firstly by the heat addition, known as Rayleigh flow, then by the nozzle to a higher exit velocity than that which occurs without the afterburner.
[src:bypass-ratio/afterburner] The mass flow is also slightly increased by the addition of the afterburner fuel.
[src:bypass-ratio/afterburner] The thrust with afterburning is 16,000 lbf (71,000 N).
[src:bypass-ratio/afterburner] The visible exhaust may show *shock diamonds*, which are caused by shock waves formed due to slight differences between ambient pressure and the exhaust pressure.
[src:bypass-ratio/afterburner] This interaction causes oscillations in the exhaust jet diameter over a short distance and causes visible banding where pressure and temperature are highest.
[src:bypass-ratio/afterburner] Thrust may be increased by burning fuel in a turbofan's cold bypass air, instead of the mixed cold and hot flows as in most afterburning turbofans.
[src:bypass-ratio/afterburner] An early augmented turbofan, the Pratt & Whitney TF30, used separate burning zones for the bypass and core flows with three of seven concentric spray rings in the bypass flow.
[src:bypass-ratio/afterburner] In comparison, the afterburning Rolls-Royce Spey used a twenty chute mixer before the fuel manifolds.
[src:bypass-ratio/afterburner] Plenum chamber burning (PCB) was partially developed for the vectored thrust Bristol Siddeley BS100 engine for the Hawker Siddeley P.1154 until the program was cancelled in 1965.
[src:bypass-ratio/afterburner] The cold bypass and hot core flows were split between two pairs of nozzles, front and rear, in the same manner as the Rolls-Royce Pegasus, and fuel was burned in the fan air before it left the front nozzles.
[src:bypass-ratio/afterburner] It would have given greater thrust for take-off and supersonic performance in an aircraft similar to, but bigger than, the Hawker Siddeley Harrier.
[src:bypass-ratio/afterburner] Duct heating was used by Pratt & Whitney for their JTF17 turbofan proposal for the U.S.
[src:bypass-ratio/afterburner] Supersonic Transport Program in 1964 and a demonstrator engine was run.
[src:bypass-ratio/afterburner] The duct heater used an annular combustor and would be used for takeoff, climb and cruise at Mach 2.7 with different amounts of augmentation depending on aircraft weight.
[src:bypass-ratio/afterburner] A jet engine afterburner is an extended exhaust section containing extra fuel injectors.
[src:bypass-ratio/afterburner] Since the jet engine upstream (i.e., before the turbine) will use little of the oxygen it ingests, additional fuel can be burned after the gas flow has left the turbines.
[src:bypass-ratio/afterburner] When the afterburner is turned on, fuel is injected and igniters are fired.
[src:bypass-ratio/afterburner] The resulting combustion process increases the afterburner exit (nozzle entry) temperature, resulting in a significant increase in engine thrust.
[src:bypass-ratio/afterburner] The resulting increase in afterburner exit volume flow is accommodated by increasing the throat area of the exit nozzle.
[src:bypass-ratio/afterburner] Otherwise, if pressure is not released, the gas can flow upstream and re-ignite, possibly causing a compressor stall (or fan surge in a turbofan application).
[src:bypass-ratio/afterburner] Solar afterburners used on the F7U Cutlass, F-94 Starfire and F-89 Scorpion, had 2-position eyelid nozzles.
[src:bypass-ratio/afterburner] Modern designs incorporate not only variable-geometry (VG) nozzles but multiple stages of augmentation via separate spray bars.
[src:bypass-ratio/afterburner] To a first order, the gross thrust ratio (afterburning/dry) is directly proportional to the root of the stagnation temperature ratio across the afterburner (i.e. exit/entry).
[src:bypass-ratio/afterburner] Due to their high fuel consumption, afterburners are only used for short-duration, high-thrust requirements.
[src:bypass-ratio/afterburner] These include heavy-weight or short-runway take-offs, assisting catapult launches from aircraft carriers, and during air combat.
[src:bypass-ratio/afterburner] A notable exception is the Pratt & Whitney J58 engine used in the SR-71 Blackbird which used its afterburner for prolonged periods and was refueled in-flight as part of every reconnaissance mission.
[src:bypass-ratio/afterburner] An afterburner has a limited life to match its intermittent use.
[src:bypass-ratio/afterburner] The J58 was an exception with a continuous rating.
[src:bypass-ratio/afterburner] This was achieved with thermal barrier coatings on the liner and flame holders and by cooling the liner and nozzle with compressor bleed air instead of turbine exhaust gas.
[src:bypass-ratio/afterburner] In heat engines such as jet engines, efficiency is highest when combustion occurs at the highest pressure and temperature possible, and expanded down to ambient pressure (see Carnot cycle).
[src:bypass-ratio/afterburner] Since the exhaust gas already has a reduced oxygen content, owing to previous combustion, and since the fuel is not burning in a highly compressed air column, the afterburner is generally inefficient in comparison to the main combustion process.
[src:bypass-ratio/afterburner] Afterburner efficiency also declines significantly if, as is usually the case, the inlet and tailpipe pressure decreases with increasing altitude.
[src:bypass-ratio/afterburner] This limitation applies only to turbojets.
[src:bypass-ratio/afterburner] In a military turbofan combat engine, the bypass air is added into the exhaust, thereby increasing the core and afterburner efficiency.
[src:bypass-ratio/afterburner] In turbojets the gain is limited to 50%, whereas in a turbofan it depends on the bypass ratio and can be as much as 70%.
[src:bypass-ratio/afterburner] However, as a counterexample, the SR-71 had reasonable efficiency at high altitude in afterburning ("wet") mode owing to its high speed (Mach 3.2) and correspondingly high pressure due to ram intake.
[src:bypass-ratio/afterburner] Afterburning has a significant influence upon engine cycle choice.
[src:bypass-ratio/afterburner] Lowering the fan pressure ratio decreases specific thrust (both dry and wet afterburning), but results in a lower temperature entering the afterburner.
[src:bypass-ratio/afterburner] Since the afterburning exit temperature is effectively fixed, the temperature rise across the unit increases, raising the afterburner fuel flow.
[src:bypass-ratio/afterburner] The total fuel flow tends to increase faster than the net thrust, resulting in a higher specific fuel consumption (SFC).
[src:bypass-ratio/afterburner] However, the corresponding dry power SFC improves (i.e. lower specific thrust).
[src:bypass-ratio/afterburner] The high temperature ratio across the afterburner results in a good thrust boost.
[src:bypass-ratio/afterburner] If the aircraft burns a large percentage of its fuel with the afterburner alight, it pays to select an engine cycle with a high specific thrust (i.e. high fan pressure ratio/low bypass ratio).
[src:bypass-ratio/afterburner] The resulting engine is relatively fuel efficient with afterburning (i.e.
[src:bypass-ratio/afterburner] Combat/Take-off), but thirsty in dry power.
[src:bypass-ratio/afterburner] If, however, the afterburner is to be hardly used, a low specific thrust (low fan pressure ratio/high bypass ratio) cycle will be favored.
[src:bypass-ratio/afterburner] Such an engine has a good dry SFC, but a poor afterburning SFC at Combat/Take-off.
[src:bypass-ratio/afterburner] Often the engine designer is faced with a compromise between these two extremes.
[src:bypass-ratio/afterburner] The Caproni Campini C.C.2 motorjet, designed by the Italian engineer Secondo Campini, was the first aircraft to incorporate an afterburner.
[src:bypass-ratio/afterburner] The first flight of a C.C.2, with its afterburners operating, took place on 11 April 1941.
[src:bypass-ratio/afterburner] Early British afterburner ("reheat") work included flight tests on a Rolls-Royce W2/B23 in a Gloster Meteor I in late 1944 and ground tests on a Power Jets W2/700 engine in mid-1945.
[src:bypass-ratio/afterburner] This engine was destined for the Miles M.52 supersonic aircraft project.
[src:bypass-ratio/afterburner] Early American research on the concept was done by NACA, in Cleveland, Ohio, leading to the publication of the paper "Theoretical Investigation of Thrust Augmentation of Turbojet Engines by Tail-pipe Burning" in January 1947.
[src:bypass-ratio/afterburner] American work on afterburners in 1948 resulted in installations on early straight-wing jets such as the Pirate, Starfire and Scorpion.
[src:bypass-ratio/afterburner] The new Pratt & Whitney J48 turbojet, at 8,000 lbf (36 kN) thrust with afterburners, would power the Grumman swept-wing fighter F9F-6, which was about to go into production.
[src:bypass-ratio/afterburner] Other new Navy fighters with afterburners included the Chance Vought F7U-3 Cutlass, powered by two 6,000 lbf (27 kN) thrust Westinghouse J46 engines.
[src:bypass-ratio/afterburner] In the 1950s, several large afterburning engines were developed, such as the Orenda Iroquois and the British de Havilland Gyron and Rolls-Royce Avon RB.146 variants.
[src:bypass-ratio/afterburner] The Avon and its variants powered the English Electric Lightning, the first supersonic aircraft in RAF service.
[src:bypass-ratio/afterburner] The Bristol-Siddeley/Rolls-Royce Olympus was fitted with afterburners for use with the BAC TSR-2.
[src:bypass-ratio/afterburner] This system was designed and developed jointly by Bristol-Siddeley and Solar of San Diego.
[src:bypass-ratio/afterburner] The afterburner system for the Concorde was developed by Snecma.
[src:bypass-ratio/afterburner] Afterburners are generally used only in military aircraft, and are considered standard equipment on fighter aircraft.
[src:bypass-ratio/afterburner] The handful of civilian planes that have used them include some NASA research aircraft, the Tupolev Tu-144, Concorde and the White Knight of Scaled Composites.
[src:bypass-ratio/afterburner] Concorde flew long distances at supersonic speeds.
[src:bypass-ratio/afterburner] Sustained high speeds would be impossible with the high fuel consumption of afterburner, and the plane used afterburners at takeoff and to minimize time spent in the high-drag transonic flight regime.
[src:bypass-ratio/afterburner] Supersonic flight without afterburners is referred to as supercruise.
[src:bypass-ratio/afterburner] A turbojet engine equipped with an afterburner is called an "afterburning turbojet", whereas a turbofan engine similarly equipped is sometimes called an "augmented turbofan".
[src:bypass-ratio/afterburner] A "dump-and-burn" is an airshow display feature where fuel is jettisoned, then intentionally ignited using the afterburner.
[src:bypass-ratio/afterburner] A spectacular flame combined with high speed makes this a popular display for airshows, or as a finale to fireworks.
[src:bypass-ratio/afterburner] Fuel dumping is used primarily to reduce the weight of an aircraft to avoid a heavy, high-speed landing.
[src:bypass-ratio/afterburner] Other than for safety or emergency reasons, fuel dumping does not have a practical use.
[src:bypass-ratio/air-start-system] An **air-start system** is a power source used to provide the initial rotation to start large diesel engines and gas turbines.
[src:bypass-ratio/air-start-system] Compared to a gasoline (petrol) engine, a diesel engine has a very high compression ratio, an essential design feature, as it is the heat of compression that ignites the fuel.
[src:bypass-ratio/air-start-system] An electric starter with sufficient power to turn a large diesel engine would itself be so large as to be impractical so there is a need for an alternative system.
[src:bypass-ratio/air-start-system] An air start system has three main components along with various safety components, namely the air start injector, the distributor and the air receivers.
[src:bypass-ratio/air-start-system] When the system is initiated, starting air from the receivers is distributed by the distributor unit to each respective air start valve according to the firing order of the engine’s cylinders.
[src:bypass-ratio/air-start-system] Safety components include flame traps, to prevent air line explosions, a turning gear interlock which ensures that air-start cannot be initiated when the turning gear is engaged, relief valves and isolation valves, as well as drain valves at certain points along the system.
[src:bypass-ratio/air-start-system] Control components include the control valves and remote air-start valves.
[src:bypass-ratio/air-start-system] A direct start system as used on a marine slow-speed diesel is required to have up to 12 starts on a non-reversing engine or 6 starts on a reversible, or geared, engine.
[src:bypass-ratio/air-start-system] When starting the engine, compressed air is admitted to whichever cylinder has a piston just over top dead center, forcing it downward.
[src:bypass-ratio/air-start-system] As the engine starts to turn, the air-start valve on the next cylinder in line opens to continue the rotation.
[src:bypass-ratio/air-start-system] After several rotations, fuel is injected into the cylinders, the engine starts running and the air is cut off.
[src:bypass-ratio/air-start-system] To further complicate matters, a large engine is usually "blown over" first with zero fuel settings and the indicator cocks open, to prove that the engine is clear of any water build up and that everything is free to turn.
[src:bypass-ratio/air-start-system] After a successful blow ahead and a blow astern, the indicator cocks are closed on all the cylinders, and then the engine can be started on fuel.
[src:bypass-ratio/air-start-system] Significant complexity is added to the engine by using an air-start system, as the cylinder head must have an extra valve in each cylinder to admit the air in for starting, plus the required control systems.
[src:bypass-ratio/air-start-system] This added complexity and cost limits the use of air-starters to very large and expensive reciprocating engines.
[src:bypass-ratio/air-start-system] Another method of air-starting an internal combustion engine is by using compressed air or gas to drive a fluid motor in place of an electric motor.
[src:bypass-ratio/air-start-system] They can be used to start engines from 5 to 320 liters in size and if more starting power is necessary two or more motors can be used.
[src:bypass-ratio/air-start-system] Starters of this type are used in place of electric motors because of their lighter weight and higher reliability.
[src:bypass-ratio/air-start-system] They can also outlast an electric starter by a factor of three and are easier to rebuild.
[src:bypass-ratio/air-start-system] Engines operating in underground mining activities tend to operate on this type of starter system to reduce the risk of an electrical system igniting flammable material.
[src:bypass-ratio/air-start-system] All vane type air starters should have a lubricator installed to insure long-life and maximum performance.
[src:bypass-ratio/air-start-system] Lubricators give the moving parts a needed friction barrier, reduce metal corrosion and keep vanes sealed properly against the cylinder walls.
[src:bypass-ratio/air-start-system] Even the so-called lube-free air starters require lubrication to prolong trouble free life.
[src:bypass-ratio/air-start-system] Two basic lubricator devices are typically employed.
[src:bypass-ratio/air-start-system] One is an in-line or reservoir type that typically stores up to 2 quarts of lubricant, and is installed along the air supply line.
[src:bypass-ratio/air-start-system] The second style of lubricator is a small one shot device that dispenses a measured amount of lubricant every time the starter is engaged.
[src:bypass-ratio/air-start-system] Installed directly onto the air inlet of the starter, the in-line lubricators are self priming pneumatic pumps that require a 1/4″ lubrication line piped from as far away as 4 feet.
[src:bypass-ratio/air-start-system] Air Starter lubricators perform best using misting type, non-detergent oils such as diesel fuel or Marvel Mystery oil.
[src:bypass-ratio/air-start-system] If emissions are a concern, there are environmentally friendly type lubricants available on the market.
[src:bypass-ratio/air-start-system] Not all air starters require lubrication.
[src:bypass-ratio/air-start-system] Turbine type air starters do not require air motor lubrication, although some turbine air starters do use an oil filled transmission that may require periodic inspections and maintenance.
[src:bypass-ratio/air-start-system] Compressed air has been used to start gas turbine engines using air impingement starting (in which air is directed at the engine turbine blades through nozzles in the turbine casing, used on US Navy General Electric J79 engines).
[src:bypass-ratio/air-start-system] It is much more efficient to use an air turbine starter (ATS) which is usually mounted on an accessory gearbox.
[src:bypass-ratio/air-start-system] An early axial compressor turbojet had an ATS located in the compressor nose cone (eg particular variants of the J79).
[src:bypass-ratio/air-start-system] Air impingement starting was not used for US military aircraft after the F-4B, A-5A and F-5 as the pneumatic energy requirement was several times greater than when using an air turbine starter.
[src:bypass-ratio/air-start-system] The gas turbine compressor required to start a J79 with impingement starting was sufficient to start two J79 engines simultaneously in a B-58 when using air turbine starters.
[src:bypass-ratio/air-start-system] An ATS has its own turbine and gears to change its low torque and high speed to low speed and high torque at the engine mounting pad.
[src:bypass-ratio/air-start-system] Further gears in the engine gearbox connect to the engine shaft (high pressure spool on multi-spool engines).
[src:bypass-ratio/air-start-system] Compared with electric starters, air-starters have a higher power-to-weight ratio so are used on large engines as an electric starter would be too big and, with its cables, too heavy and expensive.
[src:bypass-ratio/air-start-system] However, for smaller engines, which don't need as much starter power, an electric starter is more suitable.
[src:bypass-ratio/air-start-system] It has a dual function as a generator (is known as a starter/generator) at speeds above which the engine no longer requires starter assistance.
[src:bypass-ratio/air-turborocket] The **air turborocket** is a form of combined-cycle jet engine.
[src:bypass-ratio/air-turborocket] The basic layout includes a gas generator, which produces high pressure gas, that drives a turbine/compressor assembly which compresses atmospheric air into a combustion chamber.
[src:bypass-ratio/air-turborocket] This mixture is then combusted before leaving the device through a nozzle and creating thrust.
[src:bypass-ratio/air-turborocket] There are many different types of air turborockets.
[src:bypass-ratio/air-turborocket] The various types generally differ in how the gas generator section of the engine functions.
[src:bypass-ratio/air-turborocket] Air turborockets are often referred to as **turboramjets**, **turboramjet rockets**, **turborocket expanders**, and many others.
[src:bypass-ratio/air-turborocket] As there is no consensus on which names apply to which specific concepts, various sources may use the same name for two different concepts.
[src:bypass-ratio/air-turborocket] The benefit of this setup is increased specific impulse over that of a rocket.
[src:bypass-ratio/air-turborocket] For the same carried mass of propellant as a rocket motor, the overall output of the air turborocket is much higher.
[src:bypass-ratio/air-turborocket] In addition, it provides thrust throughout a much wider speed range than a ramjet, yet is much cheaper and easier to control than a gas turbine engine.
[src:bypass-ratio/air-turborocket] The air turborocket fills a niche (in terms of cost, reliability, ruggedness, and duration of thrust) between the solid-fuel rocket motor and gas turbine engine for missile applications.
[src:bypass-ratio/air-turborocket] A **turborocket** is a type of aircraft engine combining elements of a jet engine and a rocket.
[src:bypass-ratio/air-turborocket] It typically comprises a multi-stage fan driven by a turbine, which is driven by the hot gases exhausting from a series of small rocket-like motors mounted around the turbine inlet.
[src:bypass-ratio/air-turborocket] The turbine exhaust gases mix with the fan discharge air, and combust with the air from the compressor before exhausting through a convergent-divergent propelling nozzle.
[src:bypass-ratio/air-turborocket] Once a jet engine goes high enough in an atmosphere, there is insufficient oxygen to burn the jet fuel.
[src:bypass-ratio/air-turborocket] The idea behind a turborocket is to supplement the atmospheric oxygen with an onboard supply.
[src:bypass-ratio/air-turborocket] This allows operation at a much higher altitude than a normal engine would allow.
[src:bypass-ratio/air-turborocket] The turborocket design offers a mixture of benefits with drawbacks.
[src:bypass-ratio/air-turborocket] It is not a true rocket, so it cannot operate in space.
[src:bypass-ratio/air-turborocket] Cooling the engine is not a problem because the burner and its hot exhaust gases are located behind the turbine blades.
[src:bypass-ratio/air-turborocket] The air turboramjet engine is a combined cycle engine that merges aspects of turbojet and ramjet engines.
[src:bypass-ratio/air-turborocket] The turboramjet is a hybrid engine that essentially consists of a turbojet mounted inside a ramjet.
[src:bypass-ratio/air-turborocket] The turbojet core is mounted inside a duct that contains a combustion chamber downstream of the turbojet nozzle.
[src:bypass-ratio/air-turborocket] The turboramjet can be run in turbojet mode at takeoff and during low-speed flight but then switch to ramjet mode to accelerate to high Mach numbers.
[src:bypass-ratio/air-turborocket] The operation of the engine is controlled using bypass flaps located just downstream of the diffuser.
[src:bypass-ratio/air-turborocket] During low-speed flight, controllable flaps close the bypass duct and force air directly into the compressor section of the turbojet.
[src:bypass-ratio/air-turborocket] During high-speed flight, the flaps block the flow into the turbojet, and the engine operates like a ramjet using the *aft* combustion chamber to produce thrust.
[src:bypass-ratio/air-turborocket] The engine would start out operating as a turbojet during takeoff and while climbing to altitude.
[src:bypass-ratio/air-turborocket] Upon reaching high subsonic speed, the portion of the engine downstream of the turbojet would be used as an afterburner to accelerate the plane above the speed of sound.
[src:bypass-ratio/air-turborocket] At lower speeds, air passes through an inlet and is then compressed by an axial compressor.
[src:bypass-ratio/air-turborocket] That compressor is driven by a turbine, which is powered by hot, high-pressure gas from a combustion chamber.
[src:bypass-ratio/air-turborocket] These initial aspects are very similar to how a turbojet operates, however, there are several differences.
[src:bypass-ratio/air-turborocket] The first is that the combustor in the turboramjet is often separate from the main airflow.
[src:bypass-ratio/air-turborocket] Instead of combining air from the compressor with fuel to combust, the turboramjet combustor may use hydrogen and oxygen, carried on the aircraft, as its fuel for the combustor.
[src:bypass-ratio/air-turborocket] The air compressed by the compressor bypasses the combustor and turbine section of the engine, where it is mixed with the turbine exhaust.
[src:bypass-ratio/air-turborocket] The turbine exhaust can be designed to be fuel-rich (i.e., the combustor does not burn all the fuel) which, when mixed with the compressed air, creates a hot fuel-air mixture which is ready to burn again.
[src:bypass-ratio/air-turborocket] More fuel is injected into this air where it is again combusted.
[src:bypass-ratio/air-turborocket] The exhaust is ejected through a propelling nozzle, generating thrust.
[src:bypass-ratio/air-turborocket] Picture shown lacks required bypass ducting around the compressor for ramjet operation.
[src:bypass-ratio/air-turborocket] Shown is a low bypass turbojet with re-heat.
[src:bypass-ratio/air-turborocket] The turboramjet engine is used when space is constrained, as it takes up less space than separate ramjet and turbojet engines.
[src:bypass-ratio/air-turborocket] Since a ramjet must already be traveling at high speeds before it will start working, a ramjet-powered aircraft is incapable of taking off from a runway under its own power; that is the advantage of the turbojet, which is a member of the gas turbine family of engines.
[src:bypass-ratio/air-turborocket] A turbojet does not rely purely on the motion of the engine to compress the incoming air flow; instead, the turbojet contains some additional rotating machinery that compresses incoming air and allows the engine to function during takeoff and at slow speeds.
[src:bypass-ratio/air-turborocket] In applications which stay relatively in the atmosphere and require longer durations of lower thrust over a specific speed range the air turborocket can have a weight advantage over the standard solid fuel rocket motor.
[src:bypass-ratio/air-turborocket] In terms of volumetric requirements, the rocket motor has the advantage due to the lack of inlet ducts and other air management devices.
[src:bypass-ratio/bypass-ratio] The **bypass ratio** (**BPR**) of a turbofan engine is the ratio between the mass flow rate of the bypass stream to the mass flow rate entering the core.
[src:bypass-ratio/bypass-ratio] A 10:1 bypass ratio, for example, means that 10 kg of air passes through the bypass duct for every 1 kg of air passing through the core.
[src:bypass-ratio/bypass-ratio] Turbofan engines are usually described in terms of BPR, which together with engine pressure ratio, turbine inlet temperature and fan pressure ratio are important design parameters.
[src:bypass-ratio/bypass-ratio] In addition, BPR is quoted for turboprop and unducted fan installations because their high propulsive efficiency gives them the overall efficiency characteristics of very high bypass turbofans.
[src:bypass-ratio/bypass-ratio] This allows them to be shown together with turbofans on plots which show trends of reducing specific fuel consumption (SFC) with increasing BPR.
[src:bypass-ratio/bypass-ratio] BPR is also quoted for lift fan installations where the fan airflow is remote from the engine and doesn't physically touch the engine core.
[src:bypass-ratio/bypass-ratio] Bypass provides a lower fuel consumption for the same thrust, measured as thrust specific fuel consumption (grams/second fuel per unit of thrust in kN using SI units).
[src:bypass-ratio/bypass-ratio] Lower fuel consumption that comes with high bypass ratios applies to turboprops, using a propeller rather than a ducted fan.
[src:bypass-ratio/bypass-ratio] High bypass designs are the dominant type for commercial passenger aircraft and both civilian and military jet transports.
[src:bypass-ratio/bypass-ratio] Combat aircraft use engines with **low bypass** ratios to compromise between fuel economy and the requirements of combat: high power-to-weight ratios, supersonic performance, and the ability to use afterburners.
[src:bypass-ratio/bypass-ratio] If all the gas power from a gas turbine is converted to kinetic energy in a propelling nozzle, the aircraft is best suited to high supersonic speeds.
[src:bypass-ratio/bypass-ratio] If it is all transferred to a separate large mass of air with low kinetic energy, the aircraft is best suited to zero speed (hovering).
[src:bypass-ratio/bypass-ratio] For speeds in between, the gas power is shared between a separate airstream and the gas turbine's own nozzle flow in a proportion which gives the aircraft performance required.
[src:bypass-ratio/bypass-ratio] The first jet aircraft were subsonic and the poor suitability of the propelling nozzle for these speeds due to high fuel consumption was understood, and bypass proposed, as early as 1936 (U.K.
[src:bypass-ratio/bypass-ratio] The underlying principle behind bypass is trading exhaust velocity for extra mass flow which still gives the required thrust but uses less fuel.
[src:bypass-ratio/bypass-ratio] Turbojet inventor Frank Whittle called it "gearing down the flow".
[src:bypass-ratio/bypass-ratio] Power is transferred from the gas generator to an extra mass of air, i.e. a larger diameter propelling jet, moving more slowly.
[src:bypass-ratio/bypass-ratio] The bypass spreads the available mechanical power across more air to reduce the velocity of the jet.
[src:bypass-ratio/bypass-ratio] The trade-off between mass flow and velocity is also seen with propellers and helicopter rotors by comparing disc loading and power loading.
[src:bypass-ratio/bypass-ratio] For example, the same helicopter weight can be supported by a high power engine and small diameter rotor or, for less fuel, a lower power engine and bigger rotor with lower velocity through the rotor.
[src:bypass-ratio/bypass-ratio] Bypass usually refers to transferring gas power from a gas turbine to a bypass stream of air to reduce fuel consumption and jet noise.
[src:bypass-ratio/bypass-ratio] Alternatively, there may be a requirement for an afterburning engine where the sole requirement for bypass is to provide cooling air.
[src:bypass-ratio/bypass-ratio] This sets the lower limit for BPR and these engines have been called "leaky" or continuous bleed turbojets (General Electric YJ-101 BPR 0.25) and low BPR turbojets (Pratt & Whitney PW1120).
[src:bypass-ratio/bypass-ratio] Low BPR (0.2) has also been used to provide surge margin as well as afterburner cooling for the Pratt & Whitney J58.
[src:bypass-ratio/bypass-ratio] In a zero-bypass (turbojet) engine the high temperature and high pressure exhaust gas is accelerated by expansion through a propelling nozzle and produces all the thrust.
[src:bypass-ratio/bypass-ratio] The compressor absorbs all the mechanical power produced by the turbine.
[src:bypass-ratio/bypass-ratio] In a bypass design, extra turbines drive a ducted fan that accelerates air rearward from the front of the engine.
[src:bypass-ratio/bypass-ratio] In a high-bypass design, the ducted fan and nozzle produce most of the thrust.
[src:bypass-ratio/bypass-ratio] Turbofans are closely related to turboprops in principle because both transfer some of the gas turbine's gas power, using extra machinery, to a bypass stream leaving less for the hot nozzle to convert to kinetic energy.
[src:bypass-ratio/bypass-ratio] Turbofans represent an intermediate stage between turbojets, which derive all their thrust from exhaust gases, and turbo-props which derive minimal thrust from exhaust gases (typically 10% or less).
[src:bypass-ratio/bypass-ratio] Extracting shaft power and transferring it to a bypass stream introduces extra losses which are more than made up by the improved propulsive efficiency.
[src:bypass-ratio/bypass-ratio] The turboprop at its best flight speed gives significant fuel savings over a turbojet even though an extra turbine, a gearbox and a propeller were added to the turbojet's low-loss propelling nozzle.
[src:bypass-ratio/bypass-ratio] The turbofan has additional losses from its extra turbines, fan, bypass duct and extra propelling nozzle compared to the turbojet's single nozzle.
[src:bypass-ratio/bypass-ratio] To see the influence of increasing BPR alone on overall efficiency in the aircraft, i.e.
[src:bypass-ratio/bypass-ratio] SFC, a common gas generator has to be used, i.e. no change in Brayton cycle parameters or component efficiencies.
[src:bypass-ratio/bypass-ratio] Bennett shows in this case a relatively slow rise in losses transferring power to the bypass at the same time as a fast drop in exhaust losses with a significant improvement in SFC.
[src:bypass-ratio/bypass-ratio] In reality increases in BPR over time come along with rises in gas generator efficiency masking, to some extent, the influence of BPR.
[src:bypass-ratio/bypass-ratio] A low disc loading (thrust per disc area) increases the aircraft's energy efficiency, and this reduces the fuel use.
[src:bypass-ratio/bypass-ratio] The Rolls–Royce Conway turbofan engine, developed in the early 1950s, was an early example of a bypass engine.
[src:bypass-ratio/bypass-ratio] The growth of bypass ratios during the 1960s gave jetliners fuel efficiency that could compete with that of piston-powered planes.
[src:bypass-ratio/bypass-ratio] Today (2015), most jet engines have some bypass.
[src:bypass-ratio/bypass-ratio] Modern engines in slower aircraft, such as airliners, have bypass ratios up to 12:1; in higher-speed aircraft, such as fighters, bypass ratios are much lower, around 1.5; and craft designed for speeds up to Mach 2 and somewhat above have bypass ratios below 0.5.
[src:bypass-ratio/bypass-ratio] Turboprops have bypass ratios of 50-100, although the propulsion airflow is less clearly defined for propellers than for fans and propeller airflow is slower than the airflow from turbofan nozzles.
